Josh Maoziwam 1/20/2024 2:55 PM
I look out my window and see the city from my apartment. The city's name is Avengard—I've sometimes wondered why it's called that, but I know it doesn't matter. It's interesting how people think that places deserve names. It's also interesting how people think that people deserve names. It's Wednesday, a day of the week, something which also is named by society, for whatever reason. Today is an important day, because I'll be opening the fish store. It will be named Kerloe Fishery, which is the simplest possible name to describe its function, and my presence within it. I turn away from the window, noting how many people are also waking up at the same time as I am within this city known as Avengard. On the other end of my turn is the fish tank, which I need to maintain. In doing so, the lives of the fish continue. As I give them food, their life continues, which is absolutely wonderful. Their existence barely matters at all. They're just like me. The lives of fish are truly indescribably beautiful. I pick up the fish food container, unscrew the cap of the fish food, pour the fish food into the tank, screw the cap back on, place it onto the table, then exit the bedroom. (edited)

Josh Maoziwam 1/20/2024 3:04 PM
I enter the second room of the apartment, which is a "kitchen", but I prefer to call it a fish room. Like "Kerloe Fishery", this is a much more descriptive term; rather than pretending the fish room has any individuality, I simply describe it for what it is. The reason the fish room is a fish room is, of course, because of the several fish tanks contained within it, as well as the nature of its use as a place to both cook and eat fish. I enter the final room of the apartment, the restroom. I take the toothbrush and brush my teeth, which is something I do every morning. However, I can't quite figure out why I do this. Something about that feels meaningful to me—an act that is repeated every single day, yet one that's purpose is unfathomable. I reenter the fish room, and take another tube of fish food—of which I have multiple—unscrewing it, and pouring some fish food into each of the tanks. Just like the fish in the bedroom, these fish are being kept alive by the fish food. They look different, but their function is the same. Their fate is also the same. They are worthless, yet they are more important than anything else to ever exist. I take my keys and exit my apartment, locking the door behind me. (edited)

4:00 PM
He lived in a small town. Used to be a lot bigger, but most folks moved out after a couple of corporations moved their headquarters away. Shawn grew up after that, and the town was always sleepy. He can see his childhood house from here. He can see Meryl's Convenience Store where he used to hang out after school. He can see the old library, and the old fire station, and the water tower, still in desperate need of repair.
4:02 PM
I didn't think I'd ever see these things again. More then that, I didn't think I'd ever miss them like I do right now. Back when I lived here, the only thing I ever wanted was to be somewhere else. I felt shackled, limited, like I was stuck, trapped to be the person I was for my whole life.
4:08 PM
When my mom told me we were moving, I thought it was the best news I'd ever heard. I'd finally get another chance to make something of myself, to be someone who... made an impact on the world, I guess.
4:08 PM
Did I get what I wanted?
4:09 PM
I look at myself now, with my disheveled clothes and my scars and my eyepatch and my lost love and I wonder if any of it means anything.
4:12 PM

4:13 PM

4:14 PM

4:15 PM
It's been consuming me for as long as I can remember.
4:18 PM
My entire identity is constructed of context. The person called Shawn Duveldt is a construction I made in order to deal with the world, and I made it out of old comic books and video games. A lot of the time, I feel like my personhood is only skin-deep, that once you break past my skin and get down to the deeper layers that there is just truly nothing there.
4:19 PM
I've spent years trying to figure out some way to fill it in. Some way to feel like a real, complete person. That's what I hated about this place. People here would only ever know me for this constructed identity.
4:20 PM
I thought that when I moved, things would change. I would be different. But it was doomed to fail. (edited)
4:22 PM

4:22 PM

4:22 PM

Dear Lelouch, To you, I leave anything that you wish. I make this declaration because I know you would always be far too stubborn to accept any of it. You were always a deeply prideful girl, and to that I must confess I am somewhat jealous. I have purposefully left you with an enigma of an impression of what I thought of you. I need you to hate me just as much as you may love me. That sort of inescapable grasp is how I survive through you, in some cosmic sense. However, by the time you are reading this, I will be too dead to care. So allow me to end this great riddle I've left you with. I love you, Lelouch Maoziwam. You are a magnificent heir in your unceasing energy and greed. The world is incapable of understanding just how much you can force it to bend to your whims. I don't believe we'll ever be on the same page. But I can admit for certainty one simple fact. You understand love so much better than I ever have. This great enigma, an emotion entrenched within all of our spirits that defies explanation. I have no use for caring about a daughter I didn't raise to fill my shoes. I have no use caring for a hole which I used to spawn my children. And yet I do. In some incomprehensible sense, we are bound by love. Ever since your mother died, I have made it my life's work to become the villain. I am barred from love to achieve my purposes. And yet... I miss it so dearly. I want to be the father you once loved. I want to become a person someone could love. I know it's useless, and yet every inch of my being demands it. Thankfully, I don't know how to achieve it. I think you do. When I see that witch who hangs beside you, I see your mother again. Alive. I detest that I do, but it is the case. That perfume of yours, I've heard some rumours. I truly do wish you could have spread your mother's love back to me. Have the greatest life you can, You father, Shuichi Maoziwam.

He hasn’t actually lost the eye beneath it, much to the amusement of his friends, but he continues to wear it every day. Shawn has a number of friends, one of whom he’s waiting for right now.
